ocations/aftermath" title=" definition in Collocations
 ">full entry</a></span></span></span></div><div class="collapse" hclass="collapse" htag="div"><span class="unbox" id="aftermath_unbox_1" unbox="wordorigin"><span class="box_title">Word Origin</span><span class="body"><span class="p">late 15th cent. (in the farming sense of new grass growing after mowing): from the adjective <span class="eb">after</span> + dialect <span class="ei">math</span> ‘mowing’, of Germanic origin; related to German <span class="ei">Mahd</span>.</span></span></span></div>    <div id="ring-links-box">
